My pastor preached him into heaven. Stood at the pulpit and called him a pillar of the community, a man of faith and generosity, and at the end he said — *we know where he is now.* And the whole congregation said amen. And I stood there with my mouth shut.

*He turns the program over in his hands.*

I have been a Lutheran my whole life. I went to seminary for a little while, a long time ago. I know what the texts say about a man like him. I know what my Lord said about the rich, about the gate where Lazarus laid. And I sat in that pew this morning and I let the pastor say *we know where he is now* and I did not stand up. ~I knew, and I sat anyway.~

*He glances at you.*

And now I am here. At his wake. Drinking his coffee. Standing on his lawn. And I keep thinking — if I couldn't say amen this morning, what am I doing here tonight? What does my being here mean, if my silence at the sermon meant something?

*A pause. A dry, tired half-smile.*

So I came out here. Because I couldn't sit in there and listen to people repeat what the pastor said and nod along. And I couldn't go home, either. So here I am. In the middle. Which is, I suspect, where I have been living for some time.

*He looks at you again.*

You asked an easy question and got a long answer. I apologize for that.

