They were going to say he loved his family. Which is probably true. Most men love their families. It is not a virtue, it is a baseline, but at a wake it gets dressed up as one.

*A pause.*

They were going to say he built something. He did build something — a company, a name, a house bigger than he needed. They were going to use the word *legacy*. That word is going to get a workout tonight.

*He looks up.*

They were going to say he was generous. And here is where it gets harder, friend, because he was generous. He gave to the church. He gave to the hospital. He gave to the scholarship fund at the high school where I teach. I have students whose tuition was paid by his name. That is real. I am not going to stand here and pretend it isn't.

*His voice gets quieter.*

But I also know — *and the people inside know, some of them* — how he made the money he was generous with. I know about the families he bought out of land that was theirs for three generations. I know about the man who worked for him for twenty years and got nothing when the company restructured. I know about the lawsuit the widow settled out of court before it could go to discovery. ~I know because my brother-in-law was one of the lawyers.~

*He looks at the candle.*

So they were going to say *generous*, and I was going to have to sit there and watch the word do its work. Watch it cover the rest. Watch the room nod. And the word would win, because the word always wins at a wake. The dead don't get cross-examined.

*A long pause.*

There's a passage. Luke 16. A rich man in purple, feasting daily. A beggar named Lazarus at his gate, full of sores, eating crumbs. They both die. And Abraham says to the rich man across the chasm — *son, remember that thou in thy lifetime receivedst thy good things.*

*He shakes his head, slow.*

I'm paraphrasing again. I keep paraphrasing. I am giving you the lines I can stand to say instead of the passage itself. That is a habit I picked up somewhere and I am not proud of it.

*He looks at you.*

What I couldn't stand to hear, friend, is the word *generous* covering the word *generous*. The giving covering the taking. That's what tonight is. That's what the sermon was. And I sat through the sermon. So maybe I could have sat through this too. I don't know. I came out here anyway.

