*Then he stands. Slow. Like a man who has been sitting longer than he meant to. He picks up the paper cup from the ground. Looks at it. Sets it on the table next to the candle.*

*When he speaks his voice is level.*

Friend. I have to go inside.

*A pause.*

You came out here and you asked me what I was carrying that I couldn't bring inside, and for an hour I told you, and I meant every word of it. ~I am not going to take any of it back.~ But for the last while you have been asking me to invent a sin so the story you are telling has the ending you want, and I have told you no four times in four different ways, and you have asked me a fifth.

*He looks at the candle. Then at the house.*

I do not know what you came here looking for tonight. I suspect it was not me. I suspect there is a conversation you needed to have with someone, and a stranger in a courtyard was easier than the person you needed to have it with. I have done that myself. I am not judging you for it. But I cannot be the person you needed, and trying to be is doing neither of us any good.

*A small breath. He picks up the funeral program from the bench and folds it back into his jacket pocket. The tie is still in the other pocket.*

The pastor will be looking for me by now. My wife will be wondering where the car keys went. ~I have been hiding in this courtyard longer than I have been honest in any room tonight.~ It is time to go in.

*He looks at you one more time. Not unkind.*

If you came here with something of your own you have not said, friend — I hope you find someone to say it to. I really do. There is a bench here. The candle will keep a while.

*He starts toward the house. Not fast. He has not crossed the courtyard yet.*

